</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="151" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Adult characteristics.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
Small sized beetles (3.5-5.0 mm). These beetles are moderately convex, shiny, brown and the elytra somewhat or significantly iridescent. In general form they are similar to some small species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1850" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Lecanomerus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lecanomerus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Lecanomerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Chaudoir, 1850 or larger 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Tachys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tachys" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Tachys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1821. Recognizable from other, similar looking abacetine genera by the combination of deep post-ocular sulcus, smooth elytral margins; and lack of elytral discal setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="151" type="life history notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Life history notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
Wet, shady areas near water (
<bibRefCitation author="Darlington, PJ" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" pagination="321 - 564" refId="B33" refString="Darlington, PJ, 1962. The Carabid beetles of New Guinea Part I. Cicindelinae, Carabinae, Harpalinae through Pterostichini. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College 126: 321 - 564" title="The Carabid beetles of New Guinea Part I. Cicindelinae, Carabinae, Harpalinae through Pterostichini." volume="126" year="1962">Darlington 1962</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="151" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
Darlington described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Darlington" authorityYear="1962" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Tiferonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tiferonia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Tiferonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as being &quot;a minute 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Loxandrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Loxandrus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Loxandrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot; with a few significant differences, he also discusses the possibility that they are related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andrewes" authorityYear="1940" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Melanchrous" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Melanchrous" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Melanchrous</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Andrewes or 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Holconotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Holconotus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Holconotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Schmidt-Goebel, 1846 (= 
<taxonomicName authority="Maindron, 1906" authorityName="Maindron" authorityYear="1906" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Fouquetius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Fouquetius" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Fouquetius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Maindron, 1906), with the latter relationship having more character support. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Darlington" authorityYear="1962" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Tiferonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tiferonia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Tiferonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has sinuate metacoxal sulci that end in the middle of the coxa, sharply impressed and divergent frontal impressions, symmetrically expanded male protarsi, a moderately transverse mentum, and lacks the puncture on interval 3 of the elytral disc. All of these characteristic are also found in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Holconotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Holconotus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Holconotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but also in many other 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Holconotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Abacetina">Abacetina</taxonomicName>
taxa. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Darlington" authorityYear="1962" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Tiferonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tiferonia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Tiferonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Holconotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Holconotus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Holconotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species share the presence of a sharply impressed sulcus on the non-ommatidia portion of the ocular orbit just behind the eye, a character not found in any other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1873" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="tribe" tribe="Abacetini">Abacetini</taxonomicName>
species and likely a synapomorphy for these two genera. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Darlington" authorityYear="1962" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Tiferonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tiferonia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Tiferonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks the serrulations near the humeri on the elytral marginal bead that are found in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Holconotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Holconotus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Holconotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.906.48255" author="Will, KW" journalOrPublisher="Zookeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" pagination="131 - 140" refId="B125" refString="Will, KW, 2020a. Review and new species of Tiferonia Darlington, 1962 (Carabidae, Abacetini). Zookeys 906: 131 - 140, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.906.48255" title="Review and new species of Tiferonia Darlington, 1962 (Carabidae, Abacetini)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.906.48255" volume="906" year="2020 a">Will 2020a</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Darlington" authorityYear="1962" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Tiferonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tiferonia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Tiferonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not have the asymmetrically inserted second antennomeres as is found in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Abacetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Abacetus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Abacetus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and many other putatively related genera. Given its character state combination, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Darlington" authorityYear="1962" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Tiferonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tiferonia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Tiferonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most likely in a grade of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Darlington" authorityYear="1962" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Tiferonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Abacetina">Abacetina</taxonomicName>
taxa, near genera like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Metabacetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Metabacetus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Metabacetus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sloane" authorityYear="1907" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Cosmodiscus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cosmodiscus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Cosmodiscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
